// search.nx — Choice effect + pick_first + backtrack handlers (B.3 / CE)
//
// The canonical multi-shot effect substrate. `Choice` is the "given
// these options, pick one" primitive every search problem reaches for
// — N-queens, SAT, logic programming, parser combinators, regex
// alternation, type inference's instance search, refinement-types
// SMT goal direction. Per CE walkthrough §0.1: Choice is canonical
// because it's universal; only the element type differs across
// reach-for-it cases.
//
// Per the kernel's MultiShot resume discipline (primitive #2 +
// INSIGHTS L97-101): `choose` is `@resume=MultiShot` — handlers may
// resume the continuation multiple times (once per option) to
// explore alternatives. The runtime substrate that makes this
// fork-real is H7 (commits 4236b96 + ad78384 + bafd63a — LMakeContinuation
// emit path now lands continuations heap-allocated through emit_alloc).
//
// Two canonical handlers:
// - pick_first — OneShot terminal; resume with options[0]; aborts on
//   empty. Useful as a deterministic default and as a capability-stack
//   outer ("no more than one reality is explored at this boundary").
// - backtrack — MultiShot try-each; for each option, push checkpoint,
//   resume, catch Abort (means dead-end), try next. First non-abort
//   wins; the trail-rollback substrate (graph_push_checkpoint /
//   graph_rollback per src/graph.nx) reverts speculative state.
//
// Plus try_with_abort_catch — the small combinator backtrack uses to
// catch dead-ends. Per the CE walkthrough §1.3 + §4.0.2 halt-signal:
// the combinator must exist before backtrack lands cleanly; this file
// ships it alongside Choice + pick_first + backtrack to avoid
// drift mode 9 (deferred-by-omission).
//
// Per the existing substrate: `Abort` effect lives at src/types.nx:637;
// `catch_abort` handler lives at src/own.nx:31. This file COMPOSES on
// the existing substrate — does NOT redeclare Abort or catch_abort.
//
// Authority:
// - CE-choice-effect.md walkthrough §1.1 (Choice declaration), §1.2
//   (pick_first), §1.3 (backtrack), §4.0.2 (halt-signal on
//   try_with_abort_catch), QA Q-B.3.1 (bare Choice — A flows; not
//   parameterized) + QA Q-B.3.2 (handler decides empty-list semantics)
// - src/mentl_oracle.nx (commit f87abf3 — the oracle uses Choice via
//   try_each_candidate_to_queue; backtrack composes upstream when
//   candidate enumeration earns multi-shot exploration)
// - src/lower.nx + src/backends/wasm.nx (commits 4236b96 + ad78384 +
//   bafd63a — LMakeContinuation runtime substrate that this file's
//   MultiShot handlers depend on)
// - SUBSTRATE.md §"Inference IS the Light" (L50-66), §"The Continuous
//   Oracle IS Incremental Compilation Plus One Cached Value" (commit
//   636c365)

import types
import own        // for catch_abort handler

/// Choice — the canonical multi-shot effect. `choose(options)` with
/// MultiShot resume discipline. The handler decides exploration
/// policy; the call site is identical regardless. Per QA Q-B.3.1,
/// Choice is bare (NOT parameterized — Choice(Int) and Choice(String)
/// are NOT distinct row entries; the element type A flows through).
/// Per QA Q-B.3.2, runtime semantics on empty options is the handler's
/// decision (pick_first aborts; backtrack also aborts; alternative
/// handlers could surface a sentinel or deferred-search outcome).
///
/// Primitive #2 (handlers + resume discipline): MultiShot is the
/// substrate mechanism. Primitive #4 (effect row algebra): `with
/// Choice` admits the call; `!Choice` proves determinism (no fork at
/// that call site).

effect Choice {
  choose(options: List<A>) -> A                    @resume=MultiShot
}

/// pick_first — OneShot terminal handler. Per CE §1.2: resumes with
/// options[0] once and only once. Empty options performs Abort
/// (consistent with QA Q-B.3.2 empty-list-is-handler-decision; per
/// the existing Abort substrate at src/types.nx:637). Useful as a
/// deterministic default OR as a capability-stack outer ("no more
/// than one reality is explored at this boundary").
///
/// Resume discipline: the arm resumes once; the op is declared
/// MultiShot, but pick_first's INSTALLATION narrows it to OneShot
/// at this site. Row subsumption at handler install lets it pass.
/// Primitive #2's @resume=Either pattern would formalize this; for
/// V1 the narrowing is implicit in pick_first being named OneShot.

handler pick_first {
  choose(options) =>
    if options.len == 0 { perform abort() }
    else                 { resume(list_index(options, 0)) }
}

/// try_with_abort_catch — the combinator backtrack uses to catch
/// dead-ends. Composes on src/own.nx's catch_abort handler (which
/// converts abort() into None). If try_fn returns Some(value), the
/// value is used; if None (abort caught), catch_fn runs and its
/// result is used.
///
/// Per CE §1.3 + §4.0.2: this is the prerequisite substrate for
/// backtrack. The runtime shape comes from primitive #2's one-shot
/// abort + handler install; NOT a try/catch/exception reach.
///
/// Note: try_fn and catch_fn are both `with Abort` to allow the
/// outer scope's effects to flow. For backtrack's call site, both
/// thunks are closures over the surrounding `try_each` state.

fn try_with_abort_catch(try_fn, catch_fn) with Abort = {
  let attempted = (try_fn()) ~> catch_abort
  match attempted {
    Some(value)   => value,
    None          => catch_fn()
  }
}

/// backtrack — MultiShot try-each handler per CE §1.3. For each
/// option, push a checkpoint, resume the continuation with that
/// option, catch Abort to detect dead-end, rollback the trail, and
/// try the next option. Empty list propagates Abort (caller's
/// dead-end); first non-Abort outcome commits.
///
/// The trail-rollback substrate is primitive #1 — graph_push_checkpoint
/// and graph_rollback per src/graph.nx. backtrack does NOT allocate
/// per-fork state; reuses the one checkpoint-scoped trail buffer.
/// Primitive #5 (ownership as effect): options is `ref` — borrowed,
/// not consumed; each fork observes the same options list.
///
/// Composition: typically installed with a Fail handler or other
/// abort-source so the dead-end paths convert into the Abort that
/// backtrack catches. Nothing here is Prolog-specific or DPLL-
/// specific — backtrack is the substrate primitive for every "try
/// each alternative, commit the first that doesn't dead-end" pattern.

handler backtrack with Choice + GraphRead + GraphWrite + Abort {
  choose(options) => {
    fn try_each(i) =
      if i >= options.len { perform abort() }
      else {
        let checkpoint = perform graph_push_checkpoint()
        try_with_abort_catch(
          () => resume(list_index(options, i)),
          () => {
            perform graph_rollback(checkpoint)
            try_each(i + 1)
          }
        )
      }
    try_each(0)
  }
}

// ─── Connection to the kernel ─────────────────────────────────────────

/// Primitive #1 (Graph + Env) — backtrack uses graph_push_checkpoint
/// + graph_rollback (the existing graph trail substrate). Per the
/// graph_handler edits at commit a2edd50, the checkpoint stack
/// tracks active speculation depth — backtrack's per-option
/// checkpoint pushes onto the stack; rollback pops. graph_mutated
/// does NOT fire for writes inside the checkpoint (subscribers
/// would otherwise re-explore on every speculation, infinite
/// recursion).
///
/// Primitive #2 (Handlers + resume discipline) — Choice's `choose`
/// is `@resume=MultiShot`. backtrack invokes resume per-option (one
/// per call to try_each); pick_first invokes once. Per H7 substrate
/// (commits 4236b96 + ad78384 + bafd63a), MultiShot resumes are
/// heap-allocated continuation records; backtrack's per-option
/// invocation produces a fresh resume call per the existing trail
/// + checkpoint discipline.
///
/// Primitive #3 (Five verbs) — handlers compose via `~>` chain;
/// no other verbs at this level.
///
/// Primitive #4 (Effect row algebra) — `with Choice` admits the
/// `perform choose(...)` call; `!Choice` proves determinism (no
/// fork at that site). backtrack's row absorbs Choice + composes
/// with Abort + graph effects.
///
/// Primitive #5 (Ownership) — options is `ref` to backtrack
/// (borrowed by all forks); each picked option is `own` to its
/// resume scope.
///
/// Primitive #6 (Refinement) — could refine options to length >= 1
/// to compile-out empty-list aborts; V1 lets the runtime Abort handle it.
///
/// Primitive #7 (Annotation gradient) — `~> backtrack` is a
/// gradient step that unlocks search-domain capabilities (SAT, logic
/// programming, parser combinators, type inference's instance
/// search). Mentl's Teach tentacle surfaces it when the cursor's
/// row contains Choice and no terminal handler is yet installed.
///
/// Primitive #8 (Reasons) — each fork's `perform choose` records a
/// Reason (Reason::ChoiceFork(option_index)); the Why Engine walks
/// to "why this option won?" through the surviving fork's Reason
/// chain.

// ─── What this substrate refuses ──────────────────────────────────────

/// - Re-declaring Abort or catch_abort. Both already exist
///   (src/types.nx:637 + src/own.nx:31). Per Q-B.3 halt-signal:
///   compose on the existing substrate; don't redeclare.
/// - Inlining ad-hoc abort-catch inside backtrack. Per CE §4.0.2
///   halt-signal: try_with_abort_catch is the substrate combinator;
///   ships in this file alongside Choice + pick_first + backtrack
///   to avoid drift mode 9 (deferred-by-omission).
/// - Per-fork heap allocation outside the existing checkpoint trail.
///   Per primitive #1 + the H7 LMakeContinuation runtime: every
///   speculative fork goes through the SAME emit_alloc swap surface
///   as every other heap value (kernel crystallization #8 — the
///   heap has one story).
/// - Foreign vocabulary (amb, call/cc, MonadPlus, conde, miniKanren).
///   Choice is Inka's typed-resume-discipline on one effect; not a
///   port of a Scheme / Haskell / miniKanren primitive.
/// - Non-deterministic exploration order. backtrack tries options in
///   order [0, 1, 2, ...]; first non-abort wins. Determinism is
///   load-bearing for reproducibility (per the Mentl-is-100%-deterministic
///   doctrine + INSIGHTS L1011-1084 compound interest of self-reference).
